Prologue
"I beg you!" Queen Eirwen pleaded, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl closely resembled her mother. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, he had only fathered sons up to that point.
"You have two options: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is his punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He always did.
Frostfell had not always been a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. The non-magical kingdom was located in the North, while the South was a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed, and an endless war broke out between the two kingdoms until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she was to bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a single kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my king, do with me what you will, lock me up, exile me, or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen full of contempt. Perhaps, but only perhaps, he would have mercy on her. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his worst times and had given him his sons.
"Alright. The child can stay in the palace," he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the floor. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's empty rooms. He then commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution site, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution site, a loud uproar broke out among the citizens when they realized that their beloved, only queen was about to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Still others wondered why this should happen, but all were in agreement.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman who had just been a queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner set the wooden stake alight, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the room located all the way to the left in the south wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by always wondered what was in that room. They were afraid of it. Rumors spread among the maids in the palace. It was said that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room and was waiting to be let out.
Her suspicion could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory as she headed toward the south wing, while the servants walked around and whispered among themselves. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
Of course, the rumors also concerned Ivory, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" whispered Ivory in front of the intricately decorated door adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if—unlike last time—actual entry would indeed be granted. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder but immediately apologized when she realized whom she had hit.
A single knock could be heard from inside, probably to say that she was there. Where else should she be?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory had walked in without asking.
From inside, Ivory heard a knock. That probably meant a "yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound coming from a supposedly empty room, even though Ivory had been going in there for several years.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Paper was everywhere. Books were scattered around, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay about. There were no windows and little to no light. Moreover, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blankets, and was reading in one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook is that?" asked Ivory and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
